[It is sad and unfortunate some individuals lace tasty treats with toxins. The individual may have been trying to bait stray cats or dogs or even rodents. Or it may well have been intended to inflict pain on owned animals and their owners.

We like to believe our communities are safe, but unfortunately it is not always the case. Thankfully the individual took the bait and the animal to the veterinarian. Hopefully the veterinarian induced vomiting and also sent the vomit and the bait to a diagnostic lab to identify the suspicious substance.

Green bait may be one of a variety of rodenticides. Some, such as bromethalin, have almost no treatment, whereas others, such as the anticoagulant rodent baits produce at toxicosis, are more capable of being treated. So it is important to know which specific toxin the dog may have ingested to understand what the true prognosis may be. Another green substance may be strychnine. This produces convulsions and is very difficult to treat.

We certainly hope the dog is doing well. - Mod.TG

